t hassles and stress.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\"><a style=\"color: #000000;\" title=\"Iconeo\" href=\"http://www.iconeo.fr\" target=\"_blank\">Lien</a></span>\r\n\r\nFrench is spoken by more than hundred millions of native speakers, has one-hundred ninety millions non-native speakers all over the world and is an official language of twenty-nine countries. This means that you could certainly gain competitive edge once you learn this wonderful language.\r\n\r\nI am a French freelance translator and after teaching English for more than 10 years, I now offer French tutoring as well. I will provide my lessons through Skype from Monday to Saturday and I ensure to give you an interactive and enjoyable learning experience. With long years of tutoring experience, I know how to adapt my teaching and methodologies according to the needs of my clients. I have worked with many people and I have assisted them in delivering the highest quality services that will accommodate their unique requirements.\r\n\r\nOur first session is intended to get acquainted with you and create a studying plan to make sure that you get a really personalized service based on your individual requirements, whether you are searching for assistance in learning the language from the beginning or just looking for ways to enhance your French language skills. And what’s best about this first session is that it is definitely free!\r\nTake full advantage of our online private tutoring and learn or enhance your language skills in an interactive and convenient way from the comfort of your home.','Improve your French Language Skills while sitting on your couch !','','inherit','open','open','','2-revision-v1','','','2014-11-04 14:06:27','2014-11-04 13:06:27','',2,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/?p=155',0,'revision','',0),(156,1,'2014-11-04 15:22:10','2014-11-04 14:22:10','The main idea of this blog is to give you tips about French language learning and provide you with some helpful ressources you can  either use alone or during our sessions. I also wish to offer some insights on French culture and customs. \r\nFeel free to comment, ask questions or suggest topics you would like me to write about !\r\n\r\n','Bienvenue sur mon blog/ Welcome to my blog !','','publish','open','open','','bienvenue-sur-mon-blog-welcome-to-my-blog','','','2014-11-05 09:51:35','2014-11-05 08:51:35','',0,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/?p=156',0,'post','',0),(157,1,'2014-11-04 15:22:10','2014-11-04 14:22:10','The main idea of this blog is to give you tips about French language learning and provide you with some helpful ressources you can  either use alone or during our sessions. I also wish to offer some insights on French culture and customs. \r\nFeel free to comment, ask questions or suggest topics you would like me to write about !\r\n\r\n','Bienvenue sur mon blog/ Welcome to my blog !','','inherit','open','open','','156-revision-v1','','','2014-11-04 15:22:10','2014-11-04 14:22:10','',156,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/?p=157',0,'revision','',0),(158,1,'2014-11-04 15:31:40','2014-11-04 14:31:40','<strong>Listen to some French EVERY day !</strong>\r\n\r\nIt might sound obvious that no language can be learnt without regularly listening to it, yet I found out that many learners won’t listen to their targeted language for more than once a week ! And then again when they do they often stick to listening to some learning methods. Of course such cds can be useful if you plan on going to a short trip to Paris or Cannes and want to learn a few basic sentences. But those won’t prepare you for the reality of every day French language : we speak fast, use a lot of informal/colloquial words you won’t learn from those methods and most of all French has a great variety of regional accents (I’m planning on publishing a post about this last specifity pretty soon). That’s how you can spend hours learning vocabulary and grammar and end up not understanding a single word once you try to have a proper conversation with Pierre or Laurence…\r\n\r\nI’m not saying you should listen 3 hours of French each and every day because-let’s be realistic- most of us have a very busy life and a tight schedule but if you’re able to make time for a 10 to 15 minutes daily listening session I can guarantee you that you’ll make tremendous progress in the long haul.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-159 size-thumbnail\" src=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1408669936-150x150.png\" alt=\"1408669936\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>What if you’re a total beginner and don’t understand a single word of French ?</strong>\r\n\r\nWell that’s the great news : you don’t even have to understand what you’re listening to at first !\r\nThe aim is to familiarize yourself with the different sounds and accentuations of French language so you progressively are able to recognize each vowel and consonant sound and little by little recognize and understand full words. And, by listening to the same sounds over and over again, it becomes easier to imitate and reproduce them thus allowing you to get a good pronunciation, one that will make you be understood by any French speaking person. Because, once again, you can have a perfect command of French grammar and have an extensive use of French vocabulary, if you mispronounce too many words no one will understand you !\r\nSo what I would recommend if you’re beginning is to use English subtitles( or any other subtitles as long as they are in your mother tongue or a language you’re perfectly fluent in). You shouldn’t of course only focus on them and forget to listen. On the contrary I advise you to use them as a learning tool. Try to link the words you read with the sounds you hear.\r\nIf you are intermediate, you can take the next step and use French subtitles at first then no subtitles at all.\r\n\r\n<strong>What kind of media should you listen to ?</strong>\r\n\r\nAny content is good as long as it deals with a topic you’re interested in and is spoken at a normal (or slightly slower) pace. That leaves you with a wide range of possibilities : news, beauty vlogs, movies, tv shows,etc…\r\n\r\nIn my next post, I’ll introduce you to some of France’s most popular TV series so you can hopefully find one that you would like to watch and get started with your listening routine !\r\n\r\nA bientôt !','Here is my first learning advice to you','','publish','open','open','','158','','','2015-01-15 11:14:05','2015-01-15 10:14:05','',0,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/?p=158',0,'post','',0),(159,1,'2014-11-04 15:30:45','2014-11-04 14:30:45','','1408669936','','inherit','open','open','','1408669936','','','2014-11-04 15:30:45','2014-11-04 14:30:45','',158,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1408669936.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(160,1,'2014-11-04 15:31:40','2014-11-04 14:31:40','<strong>Listen to some French EVERY day !</strong>\r\n\r\nIt might sound obvious that no language can be learnt without regularly listening to it, yet I found out that many learners won’t listen to their targeted language for more than once a week ! And then again when they do they often stick to listening to some learning methods. Of course such cds can be usefull if you plan on going to a short trip to Paris or Cannes and want to learn a few basic sentences. But those won’t prepare you for the reality of every day French language : we speak fast, use a lot of informal/colloquial words you won’t learn from those methods and most of all French has a great variety of regional accents (I’m planning on publishing a post about this last specifity pretty soon). That’s how you can spend hours learning vocabulary and grammar and end up not understanding a single word once you try to have a proper conversation with Pierre or Laurence…\r\n\r\nI’m not saying you should listen 3 hours of French each and every day because, let’s be real, most of us have a very busy life and a tight schedule but if you’re able to make time for a 10 to 15 minutes daily listening session I can guarantee you that you’ll make tremendous progress in the long haul.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1408669936.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-thumbnail wp-image-159\" src=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1408669936-150x150.png\" alt=\"1408669936\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>What if you’re a total beginner and don’t understand a single word of French ?</strong>\r\n\r\nWell that’s the great news : you don’t even have to understand what you’re listening to at first !\r\nThe aim is to familiarize yourself with the different sounds and accentuations of French language so you progressively are able to recognize each vowel and consonant sound and little by little recognize and understand full words. And, by listening to the same sounds over and over again, it becomes easier to imitate and reproduce them thus allowing you to get a good pronunciation, one that will make you be understood by any French speaking person. Because, once again, you can have a perfect command of French grammar and have an extensive use of French vocabulary, if you mispronounce too many words no one will understand you !\r\nSo what I would recommend if you’re beginning is to use English subtitles( or any other subtitles as long as they are in your mother tongue or a language you’re perfectly fluent in). You shouldn’t of course only focus on them and forget to listen. On the contrary I advise you to use them as a learning tool. Try to link the words you read with the sounds you hear.\r\nIf you are intermediate, you can take the next step and use French subtitles at first then no subtitles at all.\r\n\r\n<strong>What kind of media should you listen to ?</strong>\r\n\r\nAny content is good as long as it deals with a topic you’re interested in and is spoken at a normal (or slightly slower) pace. That leaves you with a wide range of possibilities : news, beauty vlogs, movies, tv shows,etc…\r\n\r\nIn my next post, I’ll introduce you to some of France’s most popular TV series so you can hopefully find one that you would like to watch and get started with your listening routine !\r\n\r\nA bientôt !','','','inherit','open','open','','158-revision-v1','','','2014-11-04 15:31:40','2014-11-04 14:31:40','',158,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/?p=160',0,'revision','',0),(161,1,'2014-11-04 15:32:14','2014-11-04 14:32:14','<strong>Listen to some French EVERY day !</strong>\r\n\r\nIt might sound obvious that no language can be learnt without regularly listening to it, yet I found out that many learners won’t listen to their targeted language for more than once a week ! And then again when they do they often stick to listening to some learning methods. Of course such cds can be usefull if you plan on going to a short trip to Paris or Cannes and want to learn a few basic sentences. But those won’t prepare you for the reality of every day French language : we speak fast, use a lot of informal/colloquial words you won’t learn from those methods and most of all French has a great variety of regional accents (I’m planning on publishing a post about this last specifity pretty soon). That’s how you can spend hours learning vocabulary and grammar and end up not understanding a single word once you try to have a proper conversation with Pierre or Laurence…\r\n\r\nI’m not saying you should listen 3 hours of French each and every day because, let’s be real, most of us have a very busy life and a tight schedule but if you’re able to make time for a 10 to 15 minutes daily listening session I can guarantee you that you’ll make tremendous progress in the long haul.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1408669936.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-thumbnail wp-image-159\" src=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1408669936-150x150.png\" alt=\"1408669936\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>What if you’re a total beginner and don’t understand a single word of French ?</strong>\r\n\r\nWell that’s the great news : you don’t even have to understand what you’re listening to at first !\r\nThe aim is to familiarize yourself with the different sounds and accentuations of French language so you progressively are able to recognize each vowel and consonant sound and little by little recognize and understand full words. And, by listening to the same sounds over and over again, it becomes easier to imitate and reproduce them thus allowing you to get a good pronunciation, one that will make you be understood by any French speaking person. Because, once again, you can have a perfect command of French grammar and have an extensive use of French vocabulary, if you mispronounce too many words no one will understand you !\r\nSo what I would recommend if you’re beginning is to use English subtitles( or any other subtitles as long as they are in your mother tongue or a language you’re perfectly fluent in). You shouldn’t of course only focus on them and forget to listen. On the contrary I advise you to use them as a learning tool. Try to link the words you read with the sounds you hear.\r\nIf you are intermediate, you can take the next step and use French subtitles at first then no subtitles at all.\r\n\r\n<strong>What kind of media should you listen to ?</strong>\r\n\r\nAny content is good as long as it deals with a topic you’re interested in and is spoken at a normal (or slightly slower) pace. That leaves you with a wide range of possibilities : news, beauty vlogs, movies, tv shows,etc…\r\n\r\nIn my next post, I’ll introduce you to some of France’s most popular TV series so you can hopefully find one that you would like to watch and get started with your listening routine !\r\n\r\nA bientôt !','Here is my first learning advise to you ','','inherit','open','open','','158-revision-v1','','','2014-11-04 15:32:14','2014-11-04 14:32:14','',158,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/?p=161',0,'revision','',0),(162,1,'2014-11-05 10:01:33','2014-11-05 09:01:33','<strong>Listen to some French EVERY day !</strong>\r\n\r\nIt might sound obvious that no language can be learnt without regularly listening to it, yet I found out that many learners won’t listen to their targeted language for more than once a week ! And then again when they do they often stick to listening to some learning methods. Of course such cds can be useful if you plan on going to a short trip to Paris or Cannes and want to learn a few basic sentences. But those won’t prepare you for the reality of every day French language : we speak fast, use a lot of informal/colloquial words you won’t learn from those methods and most of all French has a great variety of regional accents (I’m planning on publishing a post about this last specifity pretty soon). That’s how you can spend hours learning vocabulary and grammar and end up not understanding a single word once you try to have a proper conversation with Pierre or Laurence…\r\n\r\nI’m not saying you should listen 3 hours of French each and every day because-let’s be realistic- most of us have a very busy life and a tight schedule but if you’re able to make time for a 10 to 15 minutes daily listening session I can guarantee you that you’ll make tremendous progress in the long haul.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-159 size-thumbnail\" src=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1408669936-150x150.png\" alt=\"1408669936\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>What if you’re a total beginner and don’t understand a single word of French ?</strong>\r\n\r\nWell that’s the great news : you don’t even have to understand what you’re listening to at first !\r\nThe aim is to familiarize yourself with the different sounds and accentuations of French language so you progressively are able to recognize each vowel and consonant sound and little by little recognize and understand full words. And, by listening to the same sounds over and over again, it becomes easier to imitate and reproduce them thus allowing you to get a good pronunciation, one that will make you be understood by any French speaking person. Because, once again, you can have a perfect command of French grammar and have an extensive use of French vocabulary, if you mispronounce too many words no one will understand you !\r\nSo what I would recommend if you’re beginning is to use English subtitles( or any other subtitles as long as they are in your mother tongue or a language you’re perfectly fluent in). You shouldn’t of course only focus on them and forget to listen. On the contrary I advise you to use them as a learning tool. Try to link the words you read with the sounds you hear.\r\nIf you are intermediate, you can take the next step and use French subtitles at first then no subtitles at all.\r\n\r\n<strong>What kind of media should you listen to ?</strong>\r\n\r\nAny content is good as long as it deals with a topic you’re interested in and is spoken at a normal (or slightly slower) pace. That leaves you with a wide range of possibilities : news, beauty vlogs, movies, tv shows,etc…\r\n\r\nIn my next post, I’ll introduce you to some of France’s most popular TV series so you can hopefully find one that you would like to watch and get started with your listening routine !\r\n\r\nA bientôt !\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #800080;\"><a target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: #800080;\" title=\"lien vers dfsd\" href=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/?p=96\">lesson lien</a></span>','Here is my first learning advise to you','','inherit','open','open','','158-autosave-v1','','','2014-11-05 10:01:33','2014-11-05 09:01:33','',158,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/?p=162',0,'revision','',0),(163,1,'2014-11-05 08:12:12','2014-11-05 07:12:12','<strong>Listen to some French EVERY day !</strong>\r\n\r\nIt might sound obvious that no language can be learnt without regularly listening to it, yet I found out that many learners won’t listen to their targeted language for more than once a week ! And then again when they do they often stick to listening to some learning methods. Of course such cds can be useful if you plan on going to a short trip to Paris or Cannes and want to learn a few basic sentences. But those won’t prepare you for the reality of every day French language : we speak fast, use a lot of informal/colloquial words you won’t learn from those methods and most of all French has a great variety of regional accents (I’m planning on publishing a post about this last specifity pretty soon). That’s how you can spend hours learning vocabulary and grammar and end up not understanding a single word once you try to have a proper conversation with Pierre or Laurence…\r\n\r\nI’m not saying you should listen 3 hours of French each and every day because-let’s be realistic- most of us have a very busy life and a tight schedule but if you’re able to make time for a 10 to 15 minutes daily listening session I can guarantee you that you’ll make tremendous progress in the long haul.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1408669936.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-thumbnail wp-image-159\" src=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1408669936-150x150.png\" alt=\"1408669936\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>What if you’re a total beginner and don’t understand a single word of French ?</strong>\r\n\r\nWell that’s the great news : you don’t even have to understand what you’re listening to at first !\r\nThe aim is to familiarize yourself with the different sounds and accentuations of French language so you progressively are able to recognize each vowel and consonant sound and little by little recognize and understand full words. And, by listening to the same sounds over and over again, it becomes easier to imitate and reproduce them thus allowing you to get a good pronunciation, one that will make you be understood by any French speaking person. Because, once again, you can have a perfect command of French grammar and have an extensive use of French vocabulary, if you mispronounce too many words no one will understand you !\r\nSo what I would recommend if you’re beginning is to use English subtitles( or any other subtitles as long as they are in your mother tongue or a language you’re perfectly fluent in). You shouldn’t of course only focus on them and forget to listen. On the contrary I advise you to use them as a learning tool. Try to link the words you read with the sounds you hear.\r\nIf you are intermediate, you can take the next step and use French subtitles at first then no subtitles at all.\r\n\r\n<strong>What kind of media should you listen to ?</strong>\r\n\r\nAny content is good as long as it deals with a topic you’re interested in and is spoken at a normal (or slightly slower) pace. That leaves you with a wide range of possibilities : news, beauty vlogs, movies, tv shows,etc…\r\n\r\nIn my next post, I’ll introduce you to some of France’s most popular TV series so you can hopefully find one that you would like to watch and get started with your listening routine !\r\n\r\nA bientôt !','Here is my first learning advise to you ','','inherit','open','open','','158-revision-v1','','','2014-11-05 08:12:12','2014-11-05 07:12:12','',158,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/?p=163',0,'revision','',0),(165,1,'2014-11-05 09:52:48','2014-11-05 08:52:48',' ','','','publish','open','open','','165','','','2014-12-15 21:31:11','2014-12-15 20:31:11','',0,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/?p=165',15,'nav_menu_item','',0),(166,1,'2014-11-05 09:55:32','2014-11-05 08:55:32','<strong>Listen to some French EVERY day !</strong>\r\n\r\nIt might sound obvious that no language can be learnt without regularly listening to it, yet I found out that many learners won’t listen to their targeted language for more than once a week ! And then again when they do they often stick to listening to some learning methods. Of course such cds can be useful if you plan on going to a short trip to Paris or Cannes and want to learn a few basic sentences. But those won’t prepare you for the reality of every day French language : we speak fast, use a lot of informal/colloquial words you won’t learn from those methods and most of all French has a great variety of regional accents (I’m planning on publishing a post about this last specifity pretty soon). That’s how you can spend hours learning vocabulary and grammar and end up not understanding a single word once you try to have a proper conversation with Pierre or Laurence…\r\n\r\nI’m not saying you should listen 3 hours of French each and every day because-let’s be realistic- most of us have a very busy life and a tight schedule but if you’re able to make time for a 10 to 15 minutes daily listening session I can guarantee you that you’ll make tremendous progress in the long haul.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-159 size-thumbnail\" src=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/1408669936-150x150.png\" alt=\"1408669936\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>What if you’re a total beginner and don’t understand a single word of French ?</strong>\r\n\r\nWell that’s the great news : you don’t even have to understand what you’re listening to at first !\r\nThe aim is to familiarize yourself with the different sounds and accentuations of French language so you progressively are able to recognize each vowel and consonant sound and little by little recognize and understand full words. And, by listening to the same sounds over and over again, it becomes easier to imitate and reproduce them thus allowing you to get a good pronunciation, one that will make you be understood by any French speaking person. Because, once again, you can have a perfect command of French grammar and have an extensive use of French vocabulary, if you mispronounce too many words no one will understand you !\r\nSo what I would recommend if you’re beginning is to use English subtitles( or any other subtitles as long as they are in your mother tongue or a language you’re perfectly fluent in). You shouldn’t of course only focus on them and forget to listen. On the contrary I advise you to use them as a learning tool. Try to link the words you read with the sounds you hear.\r\nIf you are intermediate, you can take the next step and use French subtitles at first then no subtitles at all.\r\n\r\n<strong>What kind of media should you listen to ?</strong>\r\n\r\nAny content is good as long as it deals with a topic you’re interested in and is spoken at a normal (or slightly slower) pace. That leaves you with a wide range of possibilities : news, beauty vlogs, movies, tv shows,etc…\r\n\r\nIn my next post, I’ll introduce you to some of France’s most popular TV series so you can hopefully find one that you would like to watch and get started with your listening routine !\r\n\r\nA bientôt !','Here is my first learning advise to you','','inherit','open','open','','158-revision-v1','','','2014-11-05 09:55:32','2014-11-05 08:55:32','',158,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/?p=166',0,'revision','',0),(167,1,'2014-11-05 10:13:17','2014-11-05 09:13:17','<h1><span style=\"color: #741dab;\">Mon titre</span></h1>\r\n<h2>lorem ipsum</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nsjdhfjshfjsdhf','Blog','','inherit','open','open','','103-autosave-v1','','','2014-11-05 10:13:17','2014-11-05 09:13:17','',103,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/103-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(169,1,'2014-11-05 19:09:44','2014-11-05 18:09:44','<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>L’anglais en quelques chiffres :</strong></span>\r\n\r\n- 3ème langue la plus parlée dans le monde\r\n- Langue officielle de 56 pays\r\n- Langue maternelle de 360 millions de personnes\r\n- 1,4 milliard de locuteurs non natifs !\r\n\r\nL’anglais est aujourd’hui LA langue du tourisme, des affaires et de la diplomatie. Ce qui en fait un outil personnel et professionnel précieux, voir indispensable.\r\n\r\nSi vous souhaitez :\r\n\r\n- Découvrir et vous initier à la langue anglaise\r\n- Reprendre les bases ou vous perfectionner\r\n- Apprendre à converser de manière fluide\r\n- Préparer un examen ou un concours\r\n- Préparer le <a href=\"http://http://www.etsglobal.org/Fr/Fre/Tests-et-preparation/Les-tests-TOEIC\">Toeic</a> (auquel j\'ai obtenu 975/990) ou le Toefl\r\n- Utiliser l’anglais dans un cadre professionnel\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Ne cherchez pas plus loin !</span></strong>\r\n\r\nTraductrice freelance, forte d’une expérience de plus de 10 ans en cours particuliers, je propose un enseignement de qualité et abordable. Je privilégie une approche interactive grâce à Skype et adapte ma méthodologie en fonction du niveau et des objectifs de chaque apprenant.\r\nLa première session, qui dure entre 30 et 50 minutes, a pour but de faire connaissance, bien comprendre vos attentes et établir ensemble un programme personnalisé. Cette première séance est bien entendu gratuite !\r\nJe propose ensuite des cours d’1h00, 1h30 ou 2h00 via Skype, du lundi au vendredi, au tarif de 19 euros de l’heure. Le règlement s’effectue de façon simple et sécurisée grâce à Paypal.\r\n\r\nPour plus d’informations, vous pouvez me contacter directement via l’onglet « contact » ou vous abonner à la newsletter pour être tenu au courant des nouveautés du blog ou des opérations promotionnelles.\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">N\'hésitez plus, start learning today !</span></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Comment ça marche ?</span></strong>\r\n\r\nPour pouvoir bénéficier de mes cours, une connexion internet haut-débit et l’installation de Skype® suffisent. Skype est un service de vidéo-conférence et de messagerie GRATUIT et qui s’installe facilement, en quelques minutes.\r\n\r\nAfin que la communication soit la plus aisée et agréable possible, vérifiez que votre ordinateur soit bien équipé d’un micro et d’un haut-parleur intégrés ou utilisez un casque-micro (vous pouvez en acquérir un pour moins de 20 euros dans n’importe quelle grande surface ou magasin d’informatique).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>Plusieurs formules s’offrent à vous :</strong></span>\r\n\r\n-     Vous n’êtes pas sûr de pouvoir être régulier ou ne souhaitez pas vous engager pour l’instant : vous pouvez tout à fait acheter des cours à l’unité ! Tarif : 22 euros de l’heure.\r\n\r\n-     Vous souhaitez prendre des cours de façon régulière : optez alors pour un pack de 5 ou 10 heures. Vous pouvez alors utiliser ces heures comme bon vous semble en réservant via le calendrier ou bien convenir avec moi d’un créneau horaire (ou plusieurs) régulier.\r\n\r\nPack de 5 heures= 100 (au lieu de 110) soit 10% de réduction.\r\nPack de 10 heures= 185 (au lieu de 220) soit 15% de réduction.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">Comment réserver une session ?</span></strong>','Apprenez/Améliorez votre anglais depuis le confort de votre domicile !','','inherit','open','open','','112-revision-v1','','','2014-11-05 19:09:44','2014-11-05 18:09:44','',112,'http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/112-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(170,1,'2014-11-05 19:14:24','2014-11-05 18:14:24','<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>L’anglais en quelques chiffres :</strong></span>\r\n\r\n- 3ème langue la plus parlée dans le monde\r\n- Langue officielle de 56 pays\r\n- Langue maternelle de 360 millions de personnes\r\n- 1,4 milliard de locuteurs non natifs !\r\n\r\nL’anglais est aujourd’hui LA langue du tourisme, des affaires et de la diplomatie. Ce qui en fait un outil personnel et professionnel précieux, voir indispensable.\r\n\r\nSi vous souhaitez :\r\n\r\n- Découvrir et vous initier à la langue anglaise\r\n-